	A subnet mask of 255.255.255.240 (/28) defines 28 prefix bits and 4 host bits. The number of hosts in the subnet is therefore:

	24 - 2 = 14.

A network ID represents the entire class A, B, or C network. The question asked for the class A network ID because all addresses are in class A network 10.0.0.0.

	&nbsp;

	Of the incorrect answers, two list numbers that could be the subnet ID used if mask 255.255.0.0 or 255.255.255.0 were used, although the question does not give enough information for you to have calculated the subnet ID. One answer, 0.0.0.255, would never be a network or subnet ID.

IPv6 addresses can be abbreviated as follows:

	- leading 0s inside one quartet (one set of hex digits between colons) - remove the leading 0s

	- A single quartet of 0s&rsquo; (0000) - abbreviate as a single 0

	- Multiple consecutive quartets of all 0&rsquo;s - abbreviate as a double colon - ::

	&nbsp;

	In this case, two consecutive quartets of all 0&rsquo;s exists, so those two quartets can be abbreviated as ::. Several quartets have trailing 0&rsquo;s, which cannot be removed.&nbsp;

	&nbsp;

	The two incorrect answers are invalid abbreviations because they have removed trailing 0s inside a quartet, which is not allowed. One incorrect answer removes trailing 0s in the first quartet, and the other incorrect answer removes trailing 0s from the 7th quartet .

	&nbsp;

	The two correct answers, which show correct abbreviations, abbreviate the two consecutive all 0 quartets in two ways. One uses the optimal choice of ::, while the other uses a single 0 for each quartet.

Unique Local Addresses (ULAs), like Global Unicast Addresses (GUAs), support grouping addresses into subnets and IPv6 routing. They differ in that ULAs rely on a random self-assignment of the prefix to use, while GUAs require an administrative process to ask for and be assigned a globally-unique prefix. Also, the Internet does not allow packets to or from ULAs, as they may not be unique in the Internet due to the prefix self-assignment process. Considering these facts, the question drives us towards using ULA while ensuring each partner company uses a unique ULA prefix. ULA addresses begin with FD.

For the incorrect answers, Link-Local Addresses (LLAs) begin with FE80, multicast addresses with FF, and Global Unicast Addresses (GUAs) with 2 or 3.

&nbsp;

The ipv6 unicast-routing command toggles on the function of routing IPv6 packets. The default setting in Cisco routers, no ipv6 unicast-routing, causes the router not to route packets. 

Routers still support this command (that is, Cisco has not deprecated the command.) Also, you can configure IPv6 addresses on router interfaces with the ipv6 address command, both static and dynamic addresses, whether or not you have enabled IPv6 routing on the router.&nbsp;

